  "prompt": "Why is there no hug emoticon on WhatsApp?",
  "response": "While WhatsApp doesn't have a single, official \"hug\" emoji, there are a few reasons why this might be:\n\n* **Subjectivity of Hug Representation:** How do you visually represent a hug that everyone agrees on? Is it two stick figures embracing? Cartoon characters? Hands reaching out? It's harder to find a universally appealing and easily recognizable hug emoji than, say, a smiley face.\n* **Overlapping with Existing Emojis:** You could argue that several existing emojis already convey similar feelings of affection and support that a hug might represent. For example:\n    * \u2764\ufe0f (Red Heart)\n    * \ud83e\udd17 (Hugging Face) - This one is *closest*, even though it's just a face offering a hug.\n    * \ud83e\udec2 (People Hugging) - This emoji was added more recently and represents two people embracing, but some might find it less versatile.\n    * \ud83d\udc4d (Thumbs Up) - Can be used to show support and solidarity.\n    * \ud83d\ude4f (Folded Hands) - Can represent gratitude and support.\n* **Character Limit and Emoji Selection:** WhatsApp, like any platform, has to choose which emojis to include. There's a limit to the number of emojis available, and they need to prioritize those with the widest appeal and use.\n* **Dynamic Evolution of Emojis:** Emojis are constantly evolving.  The Unicode Consortium (which governs emoji standards) adds new emojis regularly.  Perhaps a more widely accepted \"hug\" emoji will be added in the future.\n\n**In summary, while the \"People Hugging\" emoji comes close, a truly universally recognized and accepted \"hug\" emoji is a challenge to design and may be deemed somewhat redundant given existing expressions of affection and support within the emoji set.**\n",
